One or two fifteenth-century manuscripts have partial translations of the Passion in southern prose, which may be portions of the above- mentioned southern translation, or may be independent fragments. 3 Two other late fourteenth— —century manuscripts have an independent translation of another part of the Meditationes—the portion

dealing with the life of our Lady.4 All these translations were certainly earlier than that

of Nicholas Love, which was the first to cover, though in an abridged form, the whole ground of the Meditationes. It became so popular that it naturally tended to oust the earlier translations, and to render fresh ones unnecessary.
